, written by specialists from many fields, grapple with the problem of a popular culture that is not very popular — but is seen by most as vital to the body politic, whether endangered by globalization or capable of politically progressive messages for its audiences. Slippery Pastimes covers a variety of topics: Canadian popular music from rock ’n’ roll to country, hip-hop to pop-Celtic; television; advertising; tourism; sport and even postage stamps! As co-editors, Nicks and Sloniowski have taken an open view of the Canadian Popular, and contributors have approached their topics from a variety of perspectives, including cultural studies, women’s studies, film studies, sociology and communication studies. The essays are accessibly written for undergraduate students and interested general readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistory. 0aPopular culturexCanada. 0aPopular culturezCanada. 0aSocial sciences. 4aCultural Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh1 aBaxter-Moore, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlundell, Valda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyko-Head, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Terrance, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCzernis, Loretta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubinsky, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEarle, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEchard, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeach, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNicks, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNicks